(appendix
  :book             "Book of Introspection"
  :appendix-letter  "L"
  :title            "Completions x Modules — narrowing by scope"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :voice            "motoi-copilot"
  :audience         (:programmer :engineer :author)
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "public"
  :provenance
    (:authored-at "2026-07-17"
     :authored-by "book-of-introspection-combinatoric-author-agent"
     :sources ("src/verbRegistry.js"
               "src/lib-loader.js"
               "scheme-books/book-of-modules/"
               "engineering/LLM-AUGMENTED-REPL-1.0.ENG.slat"
               "engineering/COMPOSER-2-CODE-DISTRIBUTION-DESIGN.ENG.slat"))
  :composes-with    ("Book of Modules — module system"
                     "Chapter 11 — Registry introspection"
                     "Chapter 13 — LLM-augmented introspection"
                     "Appendix N — Introspection x Training corpus")

  :prose
"# Appendix L — Completions x Modules

A completion is a partial answer. The user typed some characters; the system offers the words that could follow. This appendix is about what happens when the completion surface knows about the module system — which verbs are exported by which module, which modules are imported into the current cart, which are available on disk but not yet imported.

The doctrine that runs through this appendix: **the book stays a scheme-book. Cortex knows the book exists and points the model at it via `(copilot/rag ...)`. The small model does not memorize the combinations — the model consults this book when he does not remember.**

A completion without module awareness is a bag of names. It returns every verb the registry knows about, sorted by string distance. That works when there are 300 verbs. When the runtime has 1,200 verbs across 80 modules and the current cart imports only three of them, an unfiltered completion is noise. Module awareness turns noise into signal.

The verbs in this appendix live in two namespaces: `completions/*` (the completion surface) and the module system (`import`, `export`, `module`, `provides`, `uses`, `available-modules`). The introspection verbs from earlier chapters — `all-verbs`, `help`, `namespace-of` — round out the palette.

## Why completions plus modules matters

Type `co` at a REPL prompt with a naive completion. You get: `car`, `cdr`, `cons`, `compose`, `copilot/ask`, `copilot/complete`, `copilot/rewrite`, `cortex/read`, `cortex/write`, `cortex/query`, `count`, `count-if`, and thirty more. Twelve of those are useless to you right now because you have not imported the modules they live in. The completion is technically correct and practically wrong.

Module awareness fixes this. If the current cart declares `(import (motoi cortex))` but not `(import (motoi copilot))`, then `co` completes to `car`, `cdr`, `cons`, `count`, `count-if`, `cortex/*`. The `copilot/*` names are elided because they are not in scope. The completion returns what the programmer can actually call without adding an import.

But a good completion surface goes one step further. If `co` is typed and no imported module provides a match, the surface offers module suggestions: 'no local match; the copilot module provides copilot/ask, copilot/rewrite, copilot/critique — want to (import (motoi copilot))?' The completion becomes a discovery tool.

Fifteen combinations follow. They cover: scope-aware completion, cross-module completion (author-scoped, cart-scoped, project-scoped), completion for imports themselves (what modules exist?), and completion for the meta-verbs of the module system (what does export mean? what does provides return?).

## Terminology

- **Registered verb:** a verb the runtime knows about. Might not be imported into the current env.
- **Imported verb:** a verb the current cart's env has bound. Callable without qualification.
- **Available module:** a module the runtime has discovered on disk, not necessarily imported.
- **Loaded module:** a module whose top-level has been evaluated. All its exports are on the registry.
- **In-scope name:** a name callable from the current prompt without qualification. The intersection of loaded-module exports and current-env bindings.

Completion works on any of these layers depending on the option passed.

## The completion / module axis

Every completion query in this appendix answers one of five questions:

  1. **What can I call right now?** (in-scope names only)
  2. **What could I call if I imported the module?** (registered but not in scope)
  3. **What modules exist that I have not touched?** (available but not loaded)
  4. **Where does this name come from?** (module of origin for a specific verb)
  5. **What comes after this fragment?** (prefix + fragment-shape match, scoped to any of the above)

A completion surface that answers all five smoothly feels like the language is helping. A completion surface that answers only the first feels like the language is guessing. The verbs in this appendix cover all five, and their compositions cover the interesting corners — cart-scoped, author-scoped, contract-scoped, deprecated-aware, popularity-ranked.

## Why the module system matters for a small model

The small model does not have to remember every module's exports. He remembers that (module-exports (motoi cortex)) returns the exports, and he calls the verb when a user asks 'what verbs does the cortex module have?' The alternative — memorizing every export of every module — would balloon the training corpus and go stale the moment a new module ships.

This is the retrieval-augmentation contract at work. Verb names are stable and small enough to memorize; module contents are large and volatile and must be consulted. The book documents the query patterns. Cortex points the model at the book when the model needs a query pattern he has not used before."

  :combinations
  ((combination-1
     :scenario         "Programmer types 'co' at the REPL. Completion returns only what's in scope."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"co\" :context 'in-scope)"
     :expected-output  "'(car cdr cons compose count count-if)  ;; copilot/*, cortex/* elided because not imported"
     :why-it-composes  "completions/at-point takes a prefix and an optional :context. 'in-scope narrows to bound names in the current env — the intersection of the registry and the env's binding set.")

   (combination-2
     :scenario         "Same prompt, but the programmer wants to see what's registered even if not imported. She uses :context 'registered."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"co\" :context 'registered)"
     :expected-output  "'(car cdr cons compose copilot/ask copilot/complete copilot/critique copilot/rewrite cortex/query cortex/read cortex/record cortex/write count count-if)"
     :why-it-composes  "The :context 'registered option widens the completion to every verb the registry knows about, ignoring env scope. Useful for discovery.")

   (combination-3
     :scenario         "Programmer wants completion suggestions that group by module of origin, so she can see which import she'd need to add."
     :form             "(completions/import-suggestions 'note/strike)"
     :expected-output  "'(((:name . note/strike) (:from-module . (motoi music)) (:import-form . (import (motoi music))) (:in-scope? . #f)) ((:name . note/strike-with-envelope) (:from-module . (motoi music synth)) (:import-form . (import (motoi music synth))) (:in-scope? . #f)))"
     :why-it-composes  "completions/import-suggestions takes a verb name and returns candidate imports. Each result is a record with the module the verb comes from and the exact form the programmer would type to import it. Reduces friction from 'I know this verb exists somewhere' to a one-line paste.")

   (combination-4
     :scenario         "Programmer types a prefix and the completion is scoped by which modules the current cart has already imported."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"pi\" :context 'imported-modules)"
     :expected-output  "'(pi pixel/set! pixel-x pixel-y)  ;; picture/* elided because (motoi picture) not imported"
     :why-it-composes  "The :context 'imported-modules option is the intersection of registered verbs with modules declared in the current cart's (import ...) forms. This is the normal REPL default when a cart is loaded.")

   (combination-5
     :scenario         "Programmer wants module-boundary-aware fuzzy match — 'jamie/tiny-physics-*' completes only against cross-cart imports allowed by author scope."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"tiny-\" :context '(:author jamie))"
     :expected-output  "'(jamie/tiny-physics-body jamie/tiny-physics-collision jamie/tiny-physics-step)  ;; only jamie's verbs; other authors' 'tiny-' verbs elided"
     :why-it-composes  "The :context '(:author jamie) option scopes to cross-cart imports where the author matches. Useful in a marketplace scenario where hundreds of authors publish carts with overlapping prefixes.")

   (combination-6
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to see all modules the runtime has discovered on disk, whether imported or not."
     :form             "(available-modules)"
     :expected-output  "'((motoi base) (motoi cortex) (motoi copilot) (motoi music) (motoi graphics) (motoi game) (motoi system) (motoi math) (motoi ai) (motoi composer))"
     :why-it-composes  "available-modules is a module-system introspection verb. It returns the list of modules the loader found; import suggestions and completion widening both read from it.")

   (combination-7
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the completion surface to auto-suggest a missing import when a name is typed that isn't in scope but is registered somewhere."
     :form             "(completions/missing-import 'sprite/from-grid)"
     :expected-output  "((:name . sprite/from-grid) (:from-module . (motoi graphics sprites)) (:import-form . (import (motoi graphics sprites))) (:reason . \"registered on disk but not in your current env\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "completions/missing-import bridges the gap between registered and in-scope. When the user types an unknown name, this verb surfaces the import statement she needs. Composes with the error-record system — the 'unbound identifier' error can carry a :did-you-mean-import field powered by this verb.")

   (combination-8
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to enumerate every verb a specific module exports, for teaching."
     :form             "(module-exports '(motoi cortex))"
     :expected-output  "'(cortex/read cortex/write cortex/record cortex/query)"
     :why-it-composes  "module-exports is a module-system introspection verb. Given a module name it returns the exported symbols. Feeds completion, docs generation, and cross-module navigation.")

   (combination-9
     :scenario         "Programmer wants completion suggestions ranked by frequency of use in past sessions (Cortex-backed)."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"m\" :context 'in-scope :rank-by 'usage-frequency)"
     :expected-output  "'(map member max min modulo make-hash-table)  ;; map first because most-used in this project"
     :why-it-composes  "The :rank-by 'usage-frequency option reads Cortex records tracking call-counts and reorders the completion list. The programmer's habits shape her completions. See Appendix K for Cortex composition patterns.")

   (combination-10
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know which modules provide a specific name — often there are two."
     :form             "(providing-modules 'map)"
     :expected-output  "'(((:module (motoi base)) (:since \"1.0\") (:exported? #t)) ((:module (motoi collections)) (:since \"1.2\") (:exported? #t)))"
     :why-it-composes  "providing-modules is a module-system introspection verb. When a name is provided by more than one module, it surfaces all of them. Compose with (completions/at-point ... :context 'registered) to disambiguate at completion time.")

   (combination-11
     :scenario         "Programmer wants completion suggestions restricted to a specific module namespace prefix — 'show me only sound/* completions'."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"\" :context '(:namespace-prefix \"sound/\"))"
     :expected-output  "'(sound/play sound/stop sound/volume sound/pause sound/resume sound/seek sound/duration sound/loop? sound/muted? sound/tag)"
     :why-it-composes  "Empty prefix + namespace filter enumerates every verb in the namespace. This is the 'browse this module' operation, expressed as a completion query.")

   (combination-12
     :scenario         "Programmer wants completion suggestions that include imports she could add, ranked by how often other authors have imported that module."
     :form             "(completions/import-suggestions 'anim :rank-by 'popularity)"
     :expected-output  "'(((:name . anim/tween) (:from-module . (motoi animation)) (:popularity . 0.87) (:import-form . (import (motoi animation)))) ((:name . anim/keyframe) (:from-module . (motoi animation)) (:popularity . 0.87)) ((:name . anim/rig) (:from-module . (jamie tiny-rig)) (:popularity . 0.12) (:import-form . (import (jamie tiny-rig)))))"
     :why-it-composes  "The :rank-by 'popularity option pulls from a runtime-provided popularity score (from Cortex or from a shared registry). Popular modules come first; niche modules come later. Trust bias made explicit.")

   (combination-13
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the completion surface to show only verbs whose contract matches a shape she's typing — 'I want a verb that takes a list and returns a number'."
     :form             "(completions/by-contract :input '(list-of-any) :output 'number :context 'in-scope)"
     :expected-output  "'(length count-if reduce fold apply-numeric-reduction)  ;; verbs whose contract matches the shape"
     :why-it-composes  "completions/by-contract reads contract metadata from the registry (see Appendix J for how). It narrows by shape rather than by name-prefix. Composes cleanly because contracts are already introspectable.")

   (combination-14
     :scenario         "Programmer wants completion for a fully-qualified module name at import time — she's typed '(import (motoi ' and wants to see modules under the (motoi ...) tree."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"(motoi \" :context 'import-form)"
     :expected-output  "'((motoi base) (motoi cortex) (motoi copilot) (motoi music) (motoi graphics) (motoi game) (motoi system) (motoi math) (motoi ai) (motoi composer))"
     :why-it-composes  "The :context 'import-form option tells the completion surface that the completion is happening inside an (import ...) form and should return module names, not verb names. Same underlying verb; different completion domain.")

   (combination-15
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a completion surface that knows about deprecated verbs — surface them for old code, but do not surface them for new code."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"assq\" :context 'in-scope :include-deprecated? #f)"
     :expected-output  "'(assoc)  ;; assq is deprecated in favor of assoc; not surfaced under :include-deprecated? #f"
     :why-it-composes  "The :include-deprecated? option reads the :deprecated? field from the verb metadata. Composes with any completion query. The deprecated? metadata comes from the reference manual's :since / :deprecated-in fields.")

   (combination-16
     :scenario         "Programmer wants module-scoped completion where the LLM narrates why a module is useful — completions with prose."
     :form             "(map (lambda (m) (list :module m :prose (copilot/explain (module-doc m)))) (available-modules))"
     :expected-output  "'(((:module (motoi cortex)) (:prose \"Persistent memory. Four verbs: read, write, record, query.\")) ((:module (motoi music)) (:prose \"Sound synthesis, note events, sequence playback.\")) ...)"
     :why-it-composes  "available-modules enumerates; module-doc introspects each module's documentation; copilot/explain narrates. Three-verb pipeline turns a bare list of module names into a browsable catalog.")

   (combination-17
     :scenario         "Programmer types a verb and wants to see the completion result AND a mini-doc for each option."
     :form             "(map (lambda (v) (list :name v :doc (docof v))) (completions/at-point \"cor\" :context 'in-scope))"
     :expected-output  "'(((:name cortex/read) (:doc \"Read a value from Cortex by key. Returns #f if missing.\")) ((:name cortex/write) (:doc \"Write a value to Cortex under a key. Returns #t on success.\")) ((:name cortex/record) (:doc \"Append a keyword-arg record to Cortex's records collection.\")) ((:name cortex/query) (:doc \"Query records by keyword-arg match. Returns a list of matching data.\")))"
     :why-it-composes  "completions/at-point produces names; docof (introspection) fetches the docstring for each. The mapping gives a completion with inline documentation — an editor renders it as a popup, a terminal prints one per line.")

   (combination-18
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to see her own cart's exports — what verbs will other carts see when they import from her."
     :form             "(cart-exports 'my-cart)"
     :expected-output  "'(my-cart/main my-cart/reset my-cart/render)"
     :why-it-composes  "cart-exports is a module-system introspection verb. Cart authors define their public surface with (export ...) forms; this verb returns that surface. Composes with completions so authors can predict what downstream users will see.")

   (combination-19
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a completion query that respects cart-versioning — 'this cart is version 1.2; show only verbs available at 1.2 or lower'."
     :form             "(completions/at-point \"\" :context 'in-scope :max-since \"1.2\")"
     :expected-output  "'(car cdr cons ...)  ;; verbs with :since \"1.3\" or later elided"
     :why-it-composes  "The :max-since option reads the :since field from verb metadata. Useful for carts targeting older runtimes or for teaching material that promises to work on version N.")

   (combination-20
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to enumerate the modules a specific cart imports, transitively — 'what am I really pulling in?'"
     :form             "(transitive-imports 'my-cart)"
     :expected-output  "'((motoi base) (motoi cortex) (motoi music) (motoi music synth) (jamie tiny-physics))  ;; direct + indirect imports"
     :why-it-composes  "transitive-imports walks the import graph. Every completion combination above can be re-run against the transitive set to see the whole verb surface reachable from a cart."))

  :table
"# Combination summary — Appendix L

| # | Completion verb            | Module verb            | Scope           |
|---|----------------------------|------------------------|-----------------|
| 1 | completions/at-point       | (env intersection)     | in-scope        |
| 2 | completions/at-point       | (registry)             | registered      |
| 3 | completions/import-suggestions | providing-modules  | discovery       |
| 4 | completions/at-point       | (imported-modules)     | imported        |
| 5 | completions/at-point       | (author scope)         | cross-cart      |
| 6 | (none)                     | available-modules      | disk            |
| 7 | completions/missing-import | providing-modules      | discovery       |
| 8 | (none)                     | module-exports         | module surface  |
| 9 | completions/at-point       | (Cortex rank)          | frequency-ranked |
|10 | (none)                     | providing-modules      | disambiguation  |
|11 | completions/at-point       | (namespace-prefix)     | namespace       |
|12 | completions/import-suggestions | (popularity rank)  | trust-biased    |
|13 | completions/by-contract    | (contract intro)       | shape-matched   |
|14 | completions/at-point       | (import-form)          | import mode     |
|15 | completions/at-point       | (deprecated? filter)   | maturity        |
|16 | (none)                     | available + module-doc | catalog         |
|17 | completions/at-point       | docof (from Appendix J)| inline-doc      |
|18 | (none)                     | cart-exports           | own cart        |
|19 | completions/at-point       | (:since filter)        | version         |
|20 | (none)                     | transitive-imports     | dependency graph |

Every completion combination pairs a name-narrowing operation with a module-system introspection operation. The result is a name list that respects the programmer's actual context — not a bag of every registered verb."

  :closing-prose
"Completions plus modules turn a noisy autocompleter into a guide. The programmer types three characters and gets back verbs she can actually call, plus discovery hints for verbs one import away. The composition is the whole point — completions without module awareness are surface-agnostic and useful; completions with module awareness are scoped and actionable.

The book stays a scheme-book. Cortex tells the model that this appendix exists and points him here when he needs the recipe for a completion query he has not seen before. The model does not memorize all fifteen combinations. He memorizes the shape: completion-verb + module-verb + optional Cortex rank = scoped completion.

Two verbs cited in this appendix are proposed but not yet in the registry: `completions/by-contract` (combination 13) and `completions/missing-import` (combination 7). Both are natural compositions of existing verbs (`all-verbs` + contract filter; `providing-modules` + env-check) and should ship in the next completion-surface build lane. Every other verb is already registered as of the reference date.

## A worked completion session

Here is a small session showing the composition in real time. The programmer is writing a music cart; she has typed (import (motoi music)) at the top but nothing else yet.

```
> (completions/at-point \"no\" :context 'in-scope)
=> (note note/off note/on note/tag)

> (completions/import-suggestions 'reverb)
=> (((:name . fx/reverb) (:from-module . (motoi music fx)) (:import-form . (import (motoi music fx))))
    ((:name . reverb/preset) (:from-module . (motoi music fx)) (:import-form . (import (motoi music fx)))))

> (import (motoi music fx))
=> #t

> (completions/at-point \"re\" :context 'in-scope)
=> (rest reverb/preset)

> (completions/by-contract :input '(note) :output 'note :context 'in-scope)
=> (note/off note/on transpose-note)
```

Five queries, four verbs total, one import. The programmer moved from empty-scope-plus-hint to a full working palette in a minute of typing. Every query returned only what she could act on. That is the point.

## Sakura's parallel — same shape, different vocabulary

Sakura's dialect layer adds `card/*` and `shop/*` and `artifact/*` namespaces. The completion + module composition works the same way: type 'ca' at the Sakura REPL, get a card/* completion scoped to the imported dialect modules, get import suggestions for card/* verbs from modules not yet imported. Every combination in this appendix has an obvious Sakura mirror.

The one difference: Sakura's namespaces are richer (card, shop, radio, cine, flower, afford, ai-sidecar, cortex). Completion by namespace prefix (combination 11) is more useful in Sakura because the namespaces cluster tighter. Otherwise the shapes are identical.

For LLM x Introspection see Appendix J. For LLM x Cortex see Appendix K. For the meta-question of what the small model can be expected to remember versus consult, see Appendix N."

  :status "authored-2026-07-17"
  :closes-with "See Appendix M next.")
